import java.util.Scanner;

public class WeekDays {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        
        System.out.print("Enter a number from 1 to 7: ");
        int day = scanner.nextInt();

        if (day == 1) {
            System.out.println("Monday");
        } else if (day == 2) {
            System.out.println("Tuesday");
        } else if (day == 3) {
            System.out.println("Wednesday");
        } else if (day == 4) {
            System.out.println("Thursday");
        } else if (day == 5) {
            System.out.println("Friday");
        } else if (day == 6) {
            System.out.println("Saturday");
        } else if (day == 7) {
            System.out.println("Sunday");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Invalid input! Please enter a number between 1 and 7.");
        }

        scanner.close();
    }
}

switch case:
cases have to be same as expressions ,must be a constant or litera
duplicate cases are not allowed
break is used to terminate the sequence
if break is not used it will continue to next case
default will execute if non of the above will execute
if default is  not at the end , put break after it

switch(expression){
  case:
    statement;
    break;
  default:
    statement;


import java.util.Scanner;

public class WeekDaysSwitch {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        
        System.out.print("Enter a number from 1 to 7: ");
        int day = scanner.nextInt();

        switch (day) {
            case 1:
                System.out.println("Monday");
                break;
            case 2:
                System.out.println("Tuesday");
                break;
            case 3:
                System.out.println("Wednesday");
                break;
            case 4:
                System.out.println("Thursday");
                break;
            case 5:
                System.out.println("Friday");
                break;
            case 6:
                System.out.println("Saturday");
                break;
            case 7:
                System.out.println("Sunday");
                break;
            default:
                System.out.println("Invalid input! Please enter a number between 1 and 7.");
                break;
        }

        scanner.close();
    }
}

ternary operator:
(condition) ? statement1 : statement2 ;
(n == 5) ? sout("yes") : sout ("no")

for each loop:
in collections we dont have index values in those situations we have use for each loop

int[] arr = {1,2,3,4,5};
for(var : arr){
  sout(var)
}
